<article id="post-7648" class="post-7648 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-europe category-fash455-course-material category-international-trade category-sourcing category-textile-industry tag-covid19 tag-eu tag-intra-region-trade">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/" rel="bookmark">EU Textile and Apparel Industry and Trade Patterns (Updated April&nbsp;2020)</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p><img data-attachment-id="7650" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/1-80/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg" data-orig-size="1422,948" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="1" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=1422" class="  wp-image-7650 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg" alt="1" width="626" height="417" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=626&amp;h=417 626w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=1252&amp;h=834 1252w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=375&amp;h=250 375w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=300&amp;h=200 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=768&amp;h=512 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/1-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=683 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /></p>
<p><strong>The EU region as a whole remains one of the world’s leading producers of textile and apparel (T&amp;A)</strong>. The value of EU’s T&amp;A production totaled EUR146.2bn in 2018, marginally up 2% from a year ago (Note: Statistical Classification of Economic Activities or NACE, sectors C13, and C14). The value of EU’s T&amp;A output was divided almost equally between textile manufacturing (EUR77.4bn) and apparel manufacturing (EUR70.0bn).</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7651" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/2-82/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg" data-orig-size="1349,766" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="2" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=1349" class="  wp-image-7651 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg" alt="2" width="602" height="341" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=602&amp;h=341 602w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=1201&amp;h=682 1201w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=440&amp;h=250 440w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=300&amp;h=170 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=768&amp;h=436 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/2-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=581 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /></p>
<p>Regarding textile production, <strong>Southern and Western EU, where most developed EU members are located such as Germany, France, and Italy, accounted for nearly 73.7% of EU’s textile manufacturing in 2018.</strong> Further, of EU countries’ total textile output, the share of non-woven and other technical textile products (NACE sectors C1395 and C1396) has increased from 19.2% in 2011 to 23.0% in 2017, which reflects the on-going structural change of the sector.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7652" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/3-63/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg" data-orig-size="1339,693" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="3" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=1339" class="  wp-image-7652 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg" alt="3" width="592" height="307" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=592&amp;h=307 592w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=1184&amp;h=614 1184w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=483&amp;h=250 483w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=300&amp;h=155 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=768&amp;h=397 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/3.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=530 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 592px) 85vw, 592px" /></p>
<p><strong>Apparel manufacturing</strong> in the EU includes two primary categories: <strong>one is the medium-priced products for consumption in the mass market</strong>, which are produced primarily by developing countries in Eastern and Southern Europe, such as Poland, Hungary, and Romania, where cheap labor is relatively abundant. <strong>The other category is the high-end luxury apparel </strong>produced by developed Western EU countries, such as Italy, UK, France, and Germany.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7653" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/9-6/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg" data-orig-size="1130,721" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="9" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=1130" class="  wp-image-7653 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg" alt="9" width="607" height="387" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=607&amp;h=387 607w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=392&amp;h=250 392w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=300&amp;h=191 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=768&amp;h=490 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=653 1024w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/9.jpg 1130w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /></p>
<p>It is also interesting to note that<strong> in Western EU countries, labor only accounted for 21.7% of the total apparel production cost in 2017</strong>, which was substantially lower than 30.1% back in 2006. This change suggests that apparel manufacturing is becoming capital and technology-intensive in some developed Western EU countries—as companies are actively adopting automation technology in garment production.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7654" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/5-25/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg" data-orig-size="1213,842" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="5" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=1213" class="  wp-image-7654 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg" alt="5" width="555" height="385" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=555&amp;h=385 555w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=1110&amp;h=770 1110w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=360&amp;h=250 360w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=300&amp;h=208 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=768&amp;h=533 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/5-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=711 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 555px) 85vw, 555px" /></p>
<p>Because of their relatively high GDP per capita and size of the population, Germany, Italy, UK, France, and Spain accounted for 61.1% of total apparel retail sales in the EU in 2018. Such a market structure has stayed stable over the past decade.</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7655" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/8-6/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg" data-orig-size="1393,533" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="8" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=1393" class="alignnone  wp-image-7655" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg" alt="8" width="644" height="246" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=644&amp;h=246 644w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=1286&amp;h=492 1286w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=500&amp;h=191 500w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=300&amp;h=115 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=768&amp;h=294 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/8.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=392 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 984px) 61vw, (max-width: 1362px) 45vw, 600px" /></p>
<p><em>Data source: UNcomtrade (2020)</em></p>
<p><strong>Intra-region trade is an important feature of the EU’s textile and apparel industry.</strong> Despite the increasing pressure from cost-competitive Asian suppliers, statistics from the World Trade Organization (WTO) show that of the EU region’s total US$73.7bn textile imports in 2018, as much as 57.1% were in the category of intra-region trade. Similarly, of EU countries’ total US$205.0bn apparel imports in 2018, as much as 48.0% also came from other EU members. In comparison, close to 97% of apparel consumed in the United States are imported in 2018, of which more than 80% came from Asia (Eurostat, 2020; WTO, 2020).</p>
<p><img data-attachment-id="7656" data-permalink="https://shenglufashion.com/2020/04/13/eu-textile-and-apparel-industry-and-trade-patterns-updated-april-2020/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1/" data-orig-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg" data-orig-size="1390,882" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="EURATEX-TC-Business-Confidence-Indicator (1)" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=1390" class="  wp-image-7656 aligncenter" src="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg" alt="EURATEX-TC-Business-Confidence-Indicator (1)" width="597" height="379" srcset="https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=597&amp;h=379 597w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=1194&amp;h=758 1194w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=394&amp;h=250 394w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=300&amp;h=190 300w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=768&amp;h=487 768w, https://shenglufashion.files.wordpress.com/2020/04/euratex-tc-business-confidence-indicator-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=650 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 597px) 85vw, 597px" /></p>
<p><strong>The EU textile and apparel industry is not immune to COVID-19. </strong><a href="https://euratex.eu/press-release/covid-19-may-cause-important-drop-in-sales-and-production/">According to the European Apparel and Textile Federation (Euratex)</a>, the outbreak of COVID-19 may cause a 50% drop in sales and production for the EU textile and apparel sector in 2020. A recent survey of EU-based T&amp;A companies shows that almost 9 out of 10 respondents reported facing serious constraints on their financial situation and 80% of companies had temporarily laid-off workers. Around 25% of surveyed companies were considering closing down their businesses. Further, EU T&amp;A companies were concerned about EU’s tightened border controls, which have “increased sharply, leading to delays in supplies but also cancelling of orders, thus aggravating the economic impact.”</p>
